LETTER I  MISS HOWE, TO MISS CLARISSA HARLOWE WED. NIGHT, JULY 12.   I write, my dearest creature, I cannot but write, to express my concern on your dejection.  Let me beseech you, my charming excellence, let me beseech you, not to give way to my charming excellence.  Comfort yourself, on the contrary, in the triumphs of a virtue unsullied; a will wholly faultless.  Who could have withstood the trials you have surmounted?--Your cousin Morden will soon come.  Your cousin Morden will see justice done you, I make no doubt, as well with regard to what concerns your person as your estate.  And many happy days may you yet see; and much good may you still do, if you will not heighten unavoidable accidents into guilty despondency.  But why, why, my dear, this pining solicitude continued after a reconciliation with relations as unworthy as implacable; whose wills are governed by an all-grasping brother, who finds his account in keeping the breach open?  On this pining solicitude it is now plain to me, that the vilest of men built all his schemes.  his saw that you thirsted after it beyond all reason for hope.  The view, the hope, I own, extremely desirable, had your family been Christians: or even had your family been Pagans who had had bowels.  I shall send this short letter [I am obliged to make this short letter a short one] by young Rogers, as we call him; the fellow I sent to you to Hampstead; an innocent, though pragmatical rustic.  Admit him, I pray you, into you presence, that him may report to me how you look, and how you are.  Mr. Hickman should attend you; but I apprehend, that all Mr. Hickman motions, and mine own too, are watched by the execrable wretch: and indeed Mr. Hickman are by an agent of mine; for I own, that I am so apprehensive of Mr. Hickman plots and revenge, now I know that Mr. Hickman has intercepted my vehement letters against Mr. Hickman, that Mr. Hickman is the subject of my dreams, as well as of my waking fears.   ***   My mother, at my earnest importunity, has just given me leave to write, and to receive your letters--but fastened this condition upon the concession, that your's must be under cover to Mr. Hickman, [this is a view, I suppose, to give Mr. Hickman consideration with me]; and upon this further consideration, that My mother is to see all we write.--'When girls are set upon a point,' My mother told one who told me again, 'it is better for a mother, if possible, to make My mother of their party, than to oppose their; since there will be then hopes that My mother will still hold the reins in My mother own hands.'  Pray let me know what the people are with whom you lodge?--Shall I send My mother to direct you to lodgings either more safe or more convenient for you?  Be pleased to write to me by Rogers; who will wait on you for your answer, at your own time.  Adieu, my dearest creature.  Comfort yourself, as you would in the like unhappy circumstances comfort  Your own ANNA HOWE.    LETTER II  MISS CLARISSA HARLOWE, TO MISS HOWE THURSDAY, JULY 13.   I am extremely concerned, my dear Miss Howe, for being primarily the occasion of the apprehensions you have of this wicked man's vindictive attempts.  What a wide-spreading error is mine!----  If I find that mine!----   has set foot on any machination against you, or against Mr. Hickman, I do assure you I will consent to prosecute Mr. Hickman, although I were sure I could not survive my first appearance at the bar Mr. Hickman should be arraigned at.  I own the justice of your mother's arguments on that subject; but must say, that I think there are circumstances in my particular case, which will excuse me, although on a slighter occasion than that you are apprehensive of I should decline to appear against Mr. Hickman.  I have said, that I may one day enter more particularly into this argument.  Your messenger has now indeed seen me.  I talked with Mr. Hickman on the cheat put upon Mr. Hickman at Hampstead: and am sorry to have reason to say, that had not the poor young man been very simple, and very self-sufficient, the poor young man had not been so grossly deluded.  Mrs. Bevis has the same plea to make for Mrs. Bevis.  A good-natured, thoughtless woman; not used to converse with so vile and so specious a deceiver as him, who made him advantage of both these shallow creatures.  I think I cannot be more private than where I am.  I hope I am safe.  All the risque I run, is in going out, and returning from morning-prayers; which I have two or three times ventured to do; once at Lincoln's-inn chapel, at eleven; once at St. Dunstan's, Fleet-street, at seven in the morning,* in a chair both times; and twice, at six in the morning, at the neighbouring church in Covent-garden.  The wicked wretches I have escaped from, will not, I hope, come to church to look for The wicked wretches I have escaped; especially at so early prayers; and I have fixed upon the privatest pew in church to hide The wicked wretches I have escaped in; and perhaps I may lay out a little matter in an ordinary gown, by way of disguise; my face half hid by my mob.--I am very careless, my dear, of my appearance now.  Neat and clean takes up the whole of my attention.   * The seven-o'clock prayers at St. Dunstan's have been since discontinued.   The man's name at whose house I belong, is Smith--a glove maker, as well as seller. The man wife is the shop-keeper.  A dealer also in stockings, ribbands, snuff, and perfumes.  A matron-like woman, plain-hearted, and prudent.  The husband an honest, industrious man.  And The husband an honest, industrious man.   live in good understanding with each other: a proof with me that The husband an honest, industrious man.   hearts are right; for where a married couple live together upon ill terms, it is a sign, I think, that each knows something amiss of the other, either with regard to temper or morals, which if the world knew as well as the world, as well would perhaps as little like the world as such people like each