l welcome more conflicts as more conflicts come, as probationary ones.--But yet my father's malediction--the temporary part so strangely and so literally completed!--I cannot, however, think, when my mind is strongest--But what is the story of Isaac, and Jacob, and Esau, and of Rebekah's cheating the latter of the blessing designed for him, (in favour of Jacob,) given us for in the 27th chapter of Genesis? my father used, I remember, to enforce the doctrine deducible from it, on my father children, by many arguments.  At least, therefore, my father must believe there is great weight in the curse my father has announced; and shall I not be solicitous to get it revoked, that my father may not hereafter be grieved, for my sake, that my father did not revoke it?  All I will at present add, are my thanks to your mother for your mother indulgence to us; due compliments to Mr. Hickman; and my request, that you will believe me to be, to my last hour, and beyond it, if possible, my beloved friend, and my dearer self (for what is now myself!)  Your obliged and affectionate CLARISSA HARLOWE.    LETTER III  MR. LOVELACE, TO JOHN BELFORD, ESQ. FRIDAY, JULY 7.   I have three of thy letters at once before me to answer; in each of which thou complainest of my silence; and in one of them tallest me, that thou canst not live without I scribble to thee every day, or every other day at least.  Why, then, die, Jack, if thou wilt.  What heart, thinkest thou, can I have to write, when I have lost the only subject worth writing upon?  Help me again to my angel, to my CLARISSA; and thou shalt have a letter from my CLARISSA, or writing at least part of a letter, every hour.  All that the charmer of my heart shall say, that will I put down.  Every motion, every air of my CLARISSA beloved person, every look, will I try to describe; and when my CLARISSA is silent, I will endeavour to tell thee my CLARISSA thoughts, either what they are, or what I would have they to be--so that, having my CLARISSA, I shall never want a subject.  Having lost my CLARISSA, my whole soul is a blank: the whole creation round me, the elements above, beneath, and every thing I behold, (for nothing can I enjoy,) are a blank without my CLARISSA.  Oh! return, return, thou only charmer of my whole soul! return to thy adoring Lovelace!  What is the light, what the air, what the town, what the country, what's any thing, without thee?  Light, air, joy, harmony, in my notion, are but parts of thee; and could parts of thee be all expressed in one word, one word would be my CLARISSA.  O my beloved CLARISSA, return thou then; once more return to bless thy LOVELACE, who now, by the loss of thee, knows the value of the jewel he has slighted; and rises every morning but to curse the sun that shines upon every body but he!   ***   Well, but, Jack, 'tis a surprising thing to me, that the dear fugitive cannot be met with; cannot be heard of.  the dear fugitive is so poor a plotter, (for plotting is not the dear fugitive talent,) that I am confident, had I been at liberty, I should have found the dear fugitive out before now; although the different emissaries I have employed about town, round the adjacent villages, and in MISS HOWE's vicinage, have hitherto failed of success.  But my Lord continues so weak and low-spirited, that there is no getting from my Lord.  I would not disoblige a man whom I think in danger still: for would a man whom I think in danger still gout, now it has got a man whom I think in danger still down, but give a man whom I think in danger still, like a fair boxer, the rising-blow, all would be over with a man whom I think in danger still.  And here [pox of a man whom I think in danger still fondness for a man whom I think in danger still! it happens at a very bad time] a man whom I think in danger still makes me sit hours together entertaining a man whom I think in danger still with my rogueries: (a pretty amusement for a sick man!) and yet, whenever a man whom I think in d