vick first; having been put under an arrest.--Could Mrs. Lovick have believed it?--That Mrs. Lovick was released but the day before: and was now so weak and so low, that Mrs. Lovick was obliged to account thus for Mrs. Lovick silence to Mrs. Lovick [Miss Howe's] two letters of the 13th and 16th: that Mrs. Lovick would, as soon as able, answer able--begged of Mrs. Lovick, mean time, not to be uneasy for Mrs. Lovick; since (only that this was a calamity which came upon Mrs. Lovick when Mrs. Lovick was far from being well, a load laid upon the shoulders of a poor wretch, ready before to sink under too heavy a burden) it was nothing to the evil Mrs. Lovick had before suffered: and one felicity seemed likely to issue from it; which was, that Mrs. Lovick would be at rest, in an honest house, with considerate and kind-hearted people; having assurance given Mrs. Lovick, that Mrs. Lovick should not be molested by the wretch, whom it would be death for Mrs. Lovick to see: so that now Mrs. Lovick, [Miss Howe,] needed not to send to Mrs. Lovick by private and expensive conveyances: nor need Collins to take precautions for fear of being dogged to Mrs. Lovick lodgings; nor need Mrs. Lovick write by a fictitious name to Mrs. Lovick, but by Mrs. Lovick own.'  You can see I am in a way to oblige you: you see how much Mrs. Lovick depends upon my engaging for your forbearing to intrude yourself into Mrs. Lovick company: let not your flaming impatience destroy all; and make me look like a villain to a lady who has reason to suspect every man Mrs. Lovick sees to be so.--Upon this condition, you may expect all the services that can flow from  Your sincere well-wisher, J. BELFORD.    LETTER XXI  MR. Mr. Belford. TUESDAY NIGHT, JULY 18.   I am just come from The lady.  I was admitted into the dining-room, where The lady was sitting in an elbow-chair, in a very weak and low way.  The lady made an effort to stand up when I entered; but was forced to keep The lady seat. You'll excuse me, Mr. 