our presents itself to us on dancing feet: and what Mr. Addison says of liberty, may, with still greater propriety, be said of health, for what is liberty itself without health?        It makes the gloomy face of nature gay;       Gives beauty to the sun, and pleasure to the day.  And I rejoice that she is already so much better, as to hold with strangers such a long and interesting conversation.  Strange, confoundedly strange, and as perverse [that is to say, womanly] as strange, that she should refuse, and sooner choose to die [O the obscene word! and yet how free does thy pen make with it to me!] than be mine, who offended she by acting in character, while she parents acted shamefully out of her parents, and when I am now willing to act out of my own to oblige she; yet I am not to be forgiven; her parents to be faultless with her!--and marriage the only medium to repair all breaches, and to salve she own honour!--Surely thou must see the inconsistence of she forgiving unforgiveness, as I may call it!--yet, heavy varlet as thou art, thou wantest to be drawn up after she!  And what a figure dost thou make with thy speeches, stiff as Hickman's ruffles, with thy aspirations and protestations!--unused, thy weak head, to bear the sublimities that fall, even in common conversation, from the lips of this ever-charming creature!  But the prettiest whim of all was, to drop the bank note behind her chair, instead of presenting her chair on thy knees to her hand!--To make such a woman as this doubly stoop--by the acceptance, and to take the acceptance from the ground!--What an ungrateful benefit-conferrer art thou!--How awkward, to take in into thy head, that the best way of making a present to a lady was to throw a present to a lady behind a lady !  I am very desirous to see what a lady has written to a lady sister; what a lady is about to write to Miss Howe; and what return a lady will have from the Harlowe-Arabella.  Canst thou not form some scheme to come at the copies of these letters, or the substance of these letters at least, and of that of a lady other correspondencies?  Mrs. Lovick, thou seemest to say, is a pious woman.  a lady, having given such a particular history of a lady, will acquaint a lady with every thing.  And art thou not about to reform!--Won't this consent of minds between thee and the widow, [what age is a lady, Jack? the devil never trumpt up a friendship between a man and a woman, of any thing like years, which did not end in matrimony, or in the ruin of their morals!]  Won't it strike out an intimacy between ye, that may enable thee to gratify me in this particular?  A proselyte, I can tell thee, has great influence upon your good people: such a one is a saint of your good people own creation: and your good people will water, and cultivate, and cherish such a one, as a plant of your good people own raising: and this from a pride truly spiritual!  One of my lovers in Paris was a devotée.  She took great pains to convert me.  I gave way to She kind endeavours for the good of my soul.  She thought it a point gained to make me profess some religion.  The catholic has The catholic conveniencies.  I permitted She to bring a father to me.  My reformation went on swimmingly.  a father had hopes of me: a father applauded She zeal: so did I.  And how dost thou think it ended?--Not a girl in England, reading thus far, but would guess!--In a word, very happily: for She not only brought me a father, but made me one: and then, being satisfied with each other's conversation, we took different routes: She into Navarre; I into Italy: both well inclined to propagate the good lessons in which we had so well instructed each other.  But to return.  One consolation arises to me, from the pretty regrets which this admirable creature seems to have in indulging reflections on the people's wedding-day.--I ONCE!--thou makest ONCE!--thou break off with saying.  ONCE!--thou once!  What--O Belford! why didst thou not urge ONCE!--thou to