lf, were it in my father himself power, would not have my father himself poor child miserable for ever.  I have the most grateful sense of my mother's goodness in sending me up my clothes.  I would have acknowledged the favour the moment I received them, with the  most thankful duty, but that I feared any line from me would be unacceptable.  I would not give fresh offence: so will decline all other commendations of duty and love: appealing to my heart for both, where both are flaming with an ardour that nothing but death can extinguish: therefore only subscribe me, without so much as a name,  My dear and happy Sister, Your afflicted servant.   A letter directed for me, at Mr. Smith's, a glover, in King-street,       Covent-garden, will come to hand.    LETTER XLVI  MR. BELFORD, TO ROBERT LOVELACE, ESQ. [IN ANSWER TO LETTERS XXIX. XXXII. OF THIS VOLUME.] EDGWARE, MONDAY, JULY 24.   What pains thou takest to persuade thyself, that the lady's ill health is owing to the vile arrest, and to the implacableness of the lady friends. Both primarily (if Both were) to be laid at thy door.  What poor excuses will good hearts make for the evils they are put upon by bad hearts!--But 'tis no wonder that he who can sit down premeditatedly to do a bad action, will content he with a bad excuse: and yet what fools must he suppose the rest of the world to be, if he imagines what fools as easy to be imposed upon as he can impose upon he?  In vain dost thou impute to pride or wilfulness the necessity to which thou hast reduced the lady of parting with the lady clothes; For can the lady do otherwise, and be the noble-minded creature the lady is?  the lady implacable friends have refused the lady the current cash the lady left behind the lady; and wished, as the lady sister wrote to her sister, to see her sister reduced to want: probably therefore Her implacable friends will not be sorry that her sister is reduced to such straights; and will take she is reduced to such straights for a just