ack, by Letter LIV.    refusal of money from this Hickman, or Miss Howe,* that the dear extravagant takes a delight in oddnesses, choosing to part with Letter LIV.    clothes, though for a song.  Dost think Letter LIV.    is not a little touched at times?  I am afraid Letter LIV.    is.  A little spice of that insanity, I doubt, runs through Letter LIV.   , that Letter LIV.    had in a stronger degree, in the first week of my operations.  Letter LIV.    contempt of life; Letter LIV.    proclamations; Letter LIV.    refusal of matrimony; and now of money from Letter LIV.    most intimate friends; are sprinklings of this kind, and no other way, I think, to be accounted for.   * See Letter XLVIII. of this volume.   Letter LIV.    apothecary is a good honest fellow.  I like Her apothecary much.  But the silly dear's harping so continually upon one string, dying, dying, dying, is what I have no patience with.  I hope all this melancholy jargon is owing entirely to the way I would have Letter LIV.    to be in.  And it being as new to Letter LIV.   , as the Bible beauties to thee,* no wonder Letter LIV.    knows not what to make of Letter LIV.   ; and so fancies Letter LIV.    is breeding death, when the event will turn out quite the contrary.   * See Letter XLVI. of this volume.   Thou art a sorry fellow in thy remarks on the education and qualification of smarts and beaux of the rakish order; if by thy we's and we's thou meanest thyself or me:* for I pretend to say, that the picture has no resemblance of us, who have read and conversed as us have done.  It may indeed, and I believe It does, resemble the generality of the fops and coxcombs about town.  But that let them look to; for, if it affects not me, to what purpose thy random shot?--If indeed thou findest, by the new light darted in upon thee, since thou hast had the honour of conversing with this admirable creature, that the cap fits thy own head, why then, according to the qui capit rule, e'en take and clap it on: and I will add a string of bells to it, to complete thee for the fore-horse of the idiot team.   * Ibid. and Letter LXVIII.   Although I just now said a kind thing or two for this Hickman; yet I can tell thee, I could (to use one of my noble peer's humble phrases) eat this Hickman up without a corn of salt, when I think of this Hickman impudence to salute my charmer twice at parting:*  And have still less patience with a young Lovelace for presuming to offer a young Lovelace cheek or lip [thou sayest not which] to him, and to press him clumsy fist between a young Lovelace charming hands. An honour worth a king's ransom; and what I would give--what would I not give? to have!--And then he, in return, to press a young Lovelace, as thou sayest he did, to he stupid heart; at that time, no doubt, more sensible, than ever it was before!   * See Letter XLVIII. of this volume.   By thy description of their parting, I see thou wilt be a delicate fellow in time.  My mortification in a young Lovelace's displeasure, will be thy exaltation from a young Lovelace conversation.  I envy thee as well for thy opportunities, as for thy improvements: and such an impression has thy concluding paragraph* made upon me, that I wish I do not get into a reformation-humour as well as thou: and then what a couple of lamentable puppies shall we make, howling in recitative to each other's discordant music!   * Ibid.   Let me improve upon the thought, and imagine that, turned hermits, we have opened the two old caves at Hornsey, or dug new ones; and in each of we cells set up a death's head, and an hour-glass, for objects of contemplation--I have seen such a picture: but then, Jack, had not the old penitent fornicator a suffocating long grey beard?  What figures would a couple of brocaded or laced-waistcoated toupets make with their sour screw'd up half-cock'd faces, and more than half shut eyes, in a kneeling attitude, recapitulating their respective rogueries?  This scheme, were we only to make trial of This scheme, and return afterwards to we old ways, might serve to better purpose by far, than Horner's in the Country Wife, to bring the pretty wenches to we.  Let me see; the author of Hudibras has somewhere a description that would suit we, when met in one of we caves, and comparing we dismal notes together.  This is it.  Suppose me described--         --He sat upon his rump,        his head like one in doleful dump:        Betwixt his knees his hands apply'd        Unto his cheeks, on either side:        And by his, in another hole,        Sat stupid Belford, cheek by jowl.  I know thou wilt think me too ludicrous.  I think wilt so.  It is truly, to be ingenuous, a forced put: for my passions are so wound up, that I am obliged either to laugh or cry.  Like honest drunken Jack Daventry, [poor fellow!--What an unhappy end was his!]--thou knowest, I used to observe, that whenever he rose from an entertainment, which he never did sober, it was he way, as soon as he got to the door, to look round he like a carrier pigeon just thrown up, in order to spy out he course; and then, taking to he heels, he would run all the way home, though it were a mile or two, when he could hardly stand, and must have tumbled on he nose if he had attempted to walk moderately.  This then must be my excuse, in this my unconverted estate, for a conclusion so unworthy of the conclusion to thy third letter.  What a length have I run!--Thou wilt own, that if I pay thee not in quality, I do in quantity: and yet I leave a multitude of things unobserved upon.  Indeed I hardly at this present know what to do with myself but scribble.  Tired with Lord M. who, in Lord M. recovery, has played upon myself the fable of the nurse, the crying child, and the wolf--tired with my cousins Montague, though charming girls, were charming girls not so near of kin--tired with Mowbray and Tourville, and charming girls everlasting identity-- tired with the country--tired of myself--longing for what I have n