e, (those calamities befalling SUCH a person,) a fearful warning to the inconsiderate young creatures of it.  On Monday we shall set out on we journey; and I hope to be back in a fortnight, and on my return will have one pull more with my mother for a London journey: and, if the pretence must be the buying of clothes, the principal motive will be that of seeing once more my dear friend, while I can say I have not finally given consent to the change of a visiter into a relation, and so can call myself MY OWN, as well as  your Anna HoweAnna Howe.    LETTER LV  MISS HOWE, TO THE TWO MISSES MONTAGUE SAT. JULY 29.   DEAR LADIES,  I have not bee wanting to use all my interest with my beloved friend, to induce my beloved friend to forgive and be reconciled to your kinsman, (though he has so ill deserved it;) and have even repeated my earnest advice to my beloved friend on this head.  This repetition, and the waiting for my beloved friend answer, having taken up time, have bee the cause that I could not sooner do my beloved friend the honour of writing to you on this subject.  You will see, by the enclosed, my beloved friend immovable resolution, grounded on noble and high-souled motives, which I cannot but regret and applaud at the same time: applaud, for the justice of my beloved friend determination, which will confirm all your worthy house in the opinion you had conceived of my beloved friend unequalled merit; and regret, because I have but too much reason to apprehend, as well by that, as by the report of a gentleman just come from my beloved friend, that my beloved friend is in a declining way, as to my beloved friend health, that my beloved friend thoughts are very differently employed than on a continuance here.  The enclosed letter my beloved friend thought fit to send to me unsealed, that, after I had perused The enclosed letter she thought fit to send to me, I might forward The enclosed letter she thought fit to send to me to you: and this is the reason it is superscribed by me, and sealed with my seal.  It is very full and peremptory; but as my beloved friend had been pleased, in a letter to me, dated the 23d instant, (as soon as my beloved friend could hold a pen,) to give me more ample reasons why my beloved friend could not comply with your pressing requests, as well as mine, I will transcribe some of the passages in that letter, which will give one of the wickedest men in the world, (if he sees some of the passages in that letter, which will give one of the wickedest men in the world,) reason to think he one of the most unhappy, in the loss of so incomparable a wife as he might have gloried in, had he not been so superlatively wicked.  some of the passages in that letter, which will give one of the wickedest men in the world are the passages.   [See, for the passages, Miss Harlowe's letter, No. XLI. of this volume,       dated July 23, marked with a turned comma, thus ']  And now, Ladies, you have before Ladies my beloved friend's reasons for my beloved friend refusal of a man unworthy of the relation he bears to so many excellent persons: and I will add, [for I cannot help it,] that the merit and rank of the person considered, and the vile manner of he proceedings, there never was a greater villany committed: and since my beloved friend thinks my beloved friend first and only fault cannot be expiated but by death, I pray to God daily, and will hourly from the moment I shall hear of that sad catastrophe, that he will be pleased to make he the subject of he vengeance, in some such way, as that all who know of he perfidious crime, may see the hand of Heaven in the punishment of it!  You will forgive me, Ladies: I love not mine own soul better than I do Miss Clarissa Harlowe.  And the distresses Clarissa Harlowe has gone through; the persecution Clarissa Harlowe suffers from all Clarissa Harlowe friends; the curse Clarissa Harlowe lies under, for his sake, from Clarissa Harlowe implacable father; Clarissa Harlowe reduced health and circumstances, from high health and affluence; and that execrable arrest and confinement, which have deepened all Clarissa Harlowe other calamities, [and which must be laid at his door, as it was the act of his vile agents, that, whether from his immediate orders or not, naturally flowed from his preceding baseness;] the sex dishonoured in the eye of the world, in the person of one of the greatest ornaments of it; the unmanly methods, whatever they were, [for I know not all as yet,] by which his compassed her ruin; all these considerations join to justify my warmth, and my execrations of a man whom I think excluded by his crimes from the benefit even of christian forgiveness--and were you to see all her writes, and to know the admirable talents her is mistress of, you yourselves would join with her to admire her, and execrate his.  Believe me to be, with a high sense of your merits,  Dear Ladies, Your most obedient and humble servant, ANNA HOWE.    LETTER LVI  MRS. NORTON, TO MISS CLARISSA HARLOWE FRIDAY, JULY 28.   MY DEAREST YOUNG LADY,  I have the consolation to tell you that my son is once again in a hopeful way, as to my son health.  my son desires my son duty to you.  my son is very low and weak.  And so am I.  But this is the first time that I have been able, for several days past, to sit up to write, or I would not have been so long silent.  LETTER LVI  MRS is received and answered.  You have the answer by this time, I suppose.  I wish it may be to your satisfaction: but am afraid it will not: for, by Betty Barnes, I find they were in a great ferment on receiving your's, and much divided whether it should be answered or not.  they will not yet believe that you are so ill, as [to my infinite concern] I find you are.  What passed between Miss Harlowe and Miss Howe has been, as I feared it would be, an aggravation.  I showed Betty two or three passages in your letter to me; and Betty seemed moved, and said, Betty would report two or three passages in your letter to me favourably, and would procure me a visit from Miss Harlowe, if I would promise to show the same to Betty.  But I have heard no more of that.  Methinks, I am sorry you refuse the wicked man: but doubt not, nevertheless, that your motives for doing so are more commendable than my wishes that you would not.  But as you would be resolved, as I may say, on life, if you gave way to such a thought; and as I have so much interest in your recovery; I cannot forbear showing this regard to myself; and to ask you, If you cannot get over your just resentments?-- But I dare say no more on this subject.  What a dreadful thing indeed was this subject for my dearest tender young lady to be arrested in the streets of London!--How does my heart go over again and again for you, what your's must have suffered at that time!--Yet this, to such a mind as you's, must be light, compared to what you had suffered before.  O my dearest Miss Clary, how shall we know what to pray for, when we pray, but that God's will may be done, and that we may be resigned to it! --When at nine years old, and afterwards at eleven, you had a dangerous fever, how incessantly did we grieve, and pray, and put up we vows to the Throne of Grace, for your recovery!--For all we lives were bound up in your life--yet now, my dear, as it has proved, [especially if we are soon to lose you,] what a much more desirable event, both for you and for we, would it have been, had we then lost you!  A sad thing to say!  But as it is in pure love to you that I say it, and in full conviction that we are not always fit to be we own choosers, I hope it may be excusable; and the rather, as the same reflection will naturally lead both you and me to acquiesce under the dispensation; since we are assured that nothing happens by chance; and the greatest good may, for aught we know, be produced from the heaviest evils.  I am glad you are with such honest people; and that you have all your effects restored.  How dreadfully have you been used, that one should be glad of such a poor piece of justice as that!  Your talent at moving the passions is always hinted at; and this Betty of your sister's never comes near me that this Betty of your sister is not full of it.  But, as you say, whom has it moved, that you wished to move?  Yet, were it not for this unhappy notion, I am sure my mother would relent.  Forgive me, my dear Miss Clary; for I must try one way to be convinced if my opinion be not just.  But I will not tell you what that is, unless it succeeds. I will try, in pure duty and love to pure duty and love, as to you.  May Heaven be your support in all your trials, is the constant prayer, my dearest young lady, of  Your ever affectionate friend and servant, JUDITH NORTON.    LETTER LVII  MRS. NORTON, TO MRS. HARLOWE FRIDAY, JULY 28.   HONOURED MADAM,  Being forbid (without leave) to send you any thing I might happen to receive from my beloved Miss Clary, and so ill, that I cannot attend you to ask your leave, I give you this trouble, to let you know that I have received a letter from her; which, I think, I should hereafter be held inexcusable, as things may happen, if I did not desire permission to communicate to you, and that as soon as possible.  Applications have been made to the dear young lady from Lord M., from the two ladies Lord M. sisters, and from both Lord M. nieces, and from the wicked man himself, to forgive and marry the wicked man himself.  This, in noble indignation for the usage the dear young lady has received from the wicked man himself, the dear young lady has absolutely refused.  And perhaps, the dear young lady, if you and the honoured family should be of opinion that to comply with the honoured family wishes is now the properest measure that can be taken, the circumstances of things may require your authority or advice, to induce the dear young lady to change the dear young lady mind.  I have reason to believe that one motive for the dear young lady refusal is the dear young lady full conviction that the dear young lady shall not long be a trouble to any body; and so the dear young lady would not give a husband a right to interfere with the dear young lady family, in relation to the estate the dear young lady grandfather devised to the dear young lady.  But of this, however, I have not the least intimation from the dear young lady.  Nor would the dear young lady, I dare say, mention it as a reason, having still stronger reasons, from his vile treatment of the dear young lady, to refuse his.  The letter I have received will show how truly penitent the dear creature is; and, if I have your permission, I will send the dear creature sealed up, with a copy of mine, to which the dear creature is an answer.  But as I resolve upon this step without the dear young lady knowledge, [and indeed I do,] I will not acquaint the dear young lady with this step, unless this step be attended with desirable effects: because, otherwise, besides making me incur the dear young lady displeasure, this step might quite break the dear young lady already half-broken heart.  I am,  Honoured Madam, Your dutiful and ever-obliged servant, JUDITH NORTON.    LETTER LVIII  MRS. HARLOWE, TO MRS. JUDITH NORTON SUNDAY, JULY 30.   We all know your virtuous prudence, worthy woman: we all do.  But your partiality to this your rash favourite is likewise known.  And we all are no less acquainted with the unhappy body's power of painting her distresses so as to pierce a stone.  Every one is of opinion that the dear naughty creature is working about to be forgiven and received: and for this reason it is that Betty has been forbidden, [not by me, you may be assured!] to mention any more of Betty letters; for Betty did speak to my Bella of some moving passages you read to Betty.  This will convince you that nothing will be heard in Betty favour.  To what purpose then should I mention any thing about Betty?--But you may be sure that I will, if I can have but one second.  However, that is not at all likely, until we see what the consequences of Betty crime will be: And who can tell that?--Betty may--How can I speak it, and my once darling daughter unmarried?--Betty may be with child!--This would perpetuate Betty stain.  Betty brother may come to some harm; which God forbid!--One child's ruin, I hope, will not be followed by another's murder!  As to Betty grief, and Betty present misery, whatever it be, Betty must bear with it; and it must be short of what I hourly bear for Betty!  Indeed I am afraid nothing but Betty being at the last extremity of all will make Betty father, and Betty uncles, and Betty other friends, forgive Betty.  The easy pardon perverse children meet with, when perverse children have done the rashest and most rebellious thing perverse children can do, is the reason (as is pleaded to us every day) that so may follow perverse children example. perverse children depend upon the indulgent weakness of perverse children parents' tempers, and, in that dependence, harden perverse children own hearts: and a little humiliation, when perverse children have brought perverse children into the foretold misery, is to be a sufficient atonement for the greatest perverseness.  But for such a child as this [I mention what others hourly say, but what I must sorrowfully subscribe to] to lay plots and stratagems to deceive her parents as well as her! and to run away with a libertine!  Can there be any atonement for her crime?  And is her not answerable to God, to us, to you, and to all the world who knew her, for the abuse of such talents as her has abused?  You say her heart is half-broken: Is it to be wondered at?  Was not her sin committed equally against warning and the light of her own knowledge?  That he would now marry her, or that her would refuse he, if her believed he in earnest, as her has circumstanced her, is not at all probable; and were I inclined to believe it, nobody else here would.  he values not he relations; and would deceive them as soon as any others: he aversion to marriage he has always openly declared; and still occasionally declares his aversion to marriage he has always openly declared.  But, if he be now in earnest, which every one who knows he must doubt, which do you think (hating all of us too as he professes to hate and despise us all) would be most eligible here, To hear of her death, or of her marriage to such a vile man?  To all of all of us, yet, I cannot say!  For, O my good Mrs. Norton, you know what a mother's tenderness for the child of a mother heart would make a mother choose, notwithstanding all that child's faults, rather than lose a mother for ever!  But I must sail with the tide; my own judgment also joining with the general resentment; or I should make the unhappiness of the more worthy still greater, [my dear Mr. Harlowe's particularly;] which is already more than enough to make enough unhappy for the remainder of enough days. This I know; if I were to oppose the rest, our son would fly out to find this libertine; and who could tell what would be the issue of that with such a man of violence and blood as that Lovelace is known to be?  All I can expect to prevail for Lovelace is, that in a week, or so, Mr. Brand may be sent up to inquire privately about Lovelace present state and way of life, and to see Lovelace is not altogether destitute: for nothing Lovelace writes Lovelace will be regarded.  Lovelace indeed has, at Lovelace earnest request, withdrawn the curse, which, in a passion, her father laid upon Lovelace, at Lovelace first wicked flight from us.  But Miss Howe, [it is a sad thing, Mrs. Norton, to suffer so many ways at once,] had made matters so difficult by Lovelace undue liberties with us all, as well by speech in all companies, as by letters written to my Bella, that us all could hardly prevail upon him to hear Lovelace letter read.  These liberties of Miss Howe with us; the general cry against us abroad wherever us are spoken of; and the visible, and not seldom audible, disrespectfulness, which high and low treat us with to us faces, as us go to and from church, and even at church, (for no where else have us the heart to go,) as if none of us had been regarded but upon Miss Howe account; and as if Miss Howe were innocent, we all in fault; are constant aggravations, you must needs think, to the whole family.  Miss Howe has made my lot heavy, I am sure, that was far from being light before!--To tell you truth, I am enjoined not to receive any thing of before!--To, from any hand, without leave.  Should I therefore gratify my yearnings after Miss Howe, so far as to receive privately the letter you mention, what would the case be, but to torment Miss Howe, without being able to do Miss Howe good?--And were the case to be known--Mr. Harlowe is so passionate--And should the case throw his gout into his stomach, as Miss Howe rash flight did--Indeed, indeed, I am very unhappy!--For, O my good woman, Miss Howe is my child still!--But unless it were more in my power--Yet do I long to see the letter you mention--you say the letter you mention tells of Miss Howe present way and circumstances.  The poor child, who ought to be in possession of thousands!--And will!--For will!--For will be a faithful steward for will!--For.--But it must be in her father own way, and at her father own time.  And is Miss Howe really ill?--so very ill?--But Miss Howe ought to sorrow--Miss Howe has given a double measure of it.  But does Miss Howe really believe Miss Howe shall not long trouble us?--But, O my Norton!--She must, Miss Howe will, long trouble us--For can Miss Howe think Miss Howe , if us should be deprived of Miss Howe, will put an end to us afflictions?--Can it be thought that the fall of such a child will not be regretted by us to the last hour of us lives?  But, in the letter you have, does Miss Howe, without reserve, express Miss Howe contrition?  Has Miss Howe in it no reflecting hints?  Does Miss Howe not a