 thou shouldst friends, who knows not how to show any.  Surely thou canst not think the cases alike--for thou shouldst, as I understand, desires but a last blessing, and a last forgiveness, for a fault in a manner involuntary, if a fault at all; and does not so much as hope to be received; thou, to be forgiven premeditated wrongs, (which, nevertheless, thou shouldst forgives, on condition to be no more molested by thee;) and hopest to be received into favour, and to make the finest jewel in the world thy absolute property in consequence of that forgiveness.  I will now briefly proceed to relate what has passed since my last, as to Smith's.  By the account I shall give thee, thou wilt see that Smith's has troubles enough upon Smith's, all springing originally from thee, without needing to add more to them by new vexations.  And as long as thou canst exert thee so very cavalierly at M. Hall, where every one is thy prisoner, I see not but the bravery of thy spirit may be as well gratified in domineering there over half a dozen persons of rank and distinction, as it could be over an helpless orphan, as I may call Smith's, since Smith's has not a single friend to stand by Smith's, if I do not; and who will think Smith's happy, if Smith's can refuge Smith's from thee, and from all the world, in the arms of death.  My last was dated on Saturday.  On Sunday, in compliance with Smith's doctor's advice, Smith's took a little airing.  Mrs. Lovick, and Mr. Smith and his wife, were with Smith's.  After being at Highgate chapel at divine service, Smith's treated Mrs. Lovick, and Mr. Smith and his wife with a little repast; and in the afternoon was at Islington church, in Smith's way home; returning tolerably cheerful.  Smith's had received several letters in my absence, as Mrs. Lovick acquainted me, besides Smith's's.  Your's, it seems, much distressed Smith's; but Smith's ordered the messenger, who pressed for an answer, to be told that it did not require an immediate one.  On Wednesday Smith's received a letter from Smith's uncle Harlowe,* in answer to one Smith's had written to Smith's mother on Saturday on Smith's knees.  It must be a very cruel one, Mrs. Lovick says, by the effects it had upon Mrs. Lovick: for, when Mrs. Lovick received it, Mrs. Lovick was intending to take an afternoon airing in a coach: but was thrown into so violent a fit of hysterics upon it, that Mrs. Lovick was forced to lie down; and (being not recovered by it) to go to bed about eight o'clock.   * See Letter LXXXIV. of this volume.   On Thursday morning Mrs. Lovick was up very early; and had recourse to the Scriptures to calm Mrs. Lovick mind, as Mrs. Lovick told Mrs. Lovick: and, weak as Mrs. Lovick was, would go in a chair to Lincoln's-inn chapel, about eleven.  Mrs. Lovick was brought home a little better; and then sat down to write to her uncle Harlowe. But was obliged to leave off several times--to struggle, as Mrs. Lovick told Mrs. Lovick, for an humble temper.  'My heart, said Mrs. Lovick to the good woman, is a proud heart, and not yet, I find, enough mortified to my condition; but, do what I can, will be for prescribing resenting things to my pen.'  I arrived in town from Belton's this Thursday evening; and went directly to Smith's's.  Mrs. Lovick was too ill to receive my visit.  But, on sending up my compliments, Mrs. Lovick sent me down word that Mrs. Lovick should be glad to see me in the morning.  Mrs. Lovick obliged me with the copy of a meditation collected by Smith's from the Scriptures.  Mrs. Lovick has entitled it Poor mortals the cause of their own misery; so entitled, I presume, with intention to take off the edge of Mrs. Lovick repinings at hardships so disproportioned to Mrs. Lovick fault, were her fault even as great as Mrs. Lovick is inclined to think her fault.  We may see, by this, the method Mrs. Lovick takes to fortify Mrs. Lovick mind, and to which Mrs. Lovick owes, in a great measure, the magnanimity with which Mrs. Lovick bears Mrs. Lovick undeserved persecutions.   MEDITATION   POOR MORTALS THE CAUSE OF THEIR OWN MISERY.  Say not thou, it is through the Lord that I fell away; for thou oughtest not to do the thing that the Lord hateth.  Say not thou, the Lord hath caused me to err; for the Lord hath no need of the sinful man.  the Lord himself made man from the beginning, and left man in the hand of man own counsel;  If thou wilt, to keep the commandments, and to perform acceptable faithfulness.  man hath set fire and water before hath: stretch forth thine hand to whither thou wilt.  man hath commanded no man to do wickedly: neither hath man given any man license to sin.  And now, the Lord, what is my hope?  Truly my hope is only in thee.  Deliver me from all my offences: and make me not a rebuke unto the foolish.  When thou with rebuke dost chasten man for sin, thou makest his beauty to consume away, like as it were a moth fretting a garment: every man, therefore, is vanity.  Turn thee unto me, and have mercy upon me; for I am desolate and afflicted.  The troubles of my heart are enlarged.  O bring thou me out of my distresses!   ***   Smith's gave me the following particulars of a conversation that passed between Smith's and a young clergyman, on Tuesday afternoon, who, as it appears, was employed to make inquiries about Smith's by Smith's friends.  He came into the shop in a riding-habit, and asked for some Spanish snuff; and finding only Mrs. Smith there, He desired to have a little talk with only Mrs. Smith there in the shop.  He beat about the bush in several distant questions, and at last began to talk more directly about Miss Harlowe.  He said He knew only Mrs. Smith there before only Mrs. Smith there fall, [that was He impudent word;] and gave the substance of the following account of only Mrs. Smith there, as I collected the following account of her from Smith's:  'only Mrs. Smith there was then, He said, the admiration and delight of every body: He lamented, with great solemnity,